column3: feature_definition
Concentration of S-sulfocysteine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
Concentration of DOPA (3,4-dihydroxyphenylalanine) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
column8: Elevated DOPA concentration in blood circulation

column3: A developmental anomnaly characterized by the lack of development of the posterior communicating artery.
The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eyelid.
The presence of a nodule (small rounded lump of tissue) in the iris.
Accumulation of antigen-bound antibody in the skin.
Enzyme activity of aromatase below the lower limit of normal.
Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by administration of phenytoin.

column2: Altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath
column3: The fibrous sheath is a structure in the midpiece of the sperm flagellum surrounding the outer dense fibers. It comprises two longitudinal columns and tranverse ribs. In case of altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath the symmetrical structure is lost, most commonly with the columns not being opposite to each other, which can be visualised by electron microscopy.

column2: Entamoeba histolytica antibody positive in stool
column3: Demonstration of antibody directed against Entamoeba histolytica in stool.
column8: Positive fecal Entamoeba histolytica antibody test

column3: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with thiamine.
Amount of keratin 14 in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
column8: Reduced keratin 14 expression in the epidermis below normal levels

column3: A history of following a vegan diet characterized by avoidance of food sourced from animals including meet, fish, and dairy products.
Any structural anomaly of the keratinocyte. The keratinocyte is the major cell type of the epidermis and is responsible for generating the protective barrier.
Sharply angled insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this feature is above the upper limit of normal.
Information about current or past medications taken by an individual.

Concentration of glutathione in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Glutathione (GSH) is an important redox active biomolecule critical in the maintenance and regulation of cellular and organismal health.
column8: Decreased red blood cell glutathione concentration

column3: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that contain a mxiture of granules and filaments.
column8: Muscle fiber cytoplasmatic inclusion bodies with mixed granules and filaments

column3: A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cytarabine.
Lymph node with increased numbers of macrophages heavily laden with lipids.
column8: Foam cells in a lymph node

column3: History of having taken a calcium channel blocker such as amlodipine, nicardipine, nifedipine, verapamil, or diltiazem.

column2: Asymmetrical insertion of the midpiece into the head
column3: Insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon on an axis that diverges from the midline axis of the spermatozoon head. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this defect is above the upper limit of normal.
A break or tear in the trachea.
The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of hyperthyroidism during the corresponding pregnancy.

column2: Reduced epidermal bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 protein expression
column3: Lower than normal amount of bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 (BP230) in the epidermis.
column8: Decreased bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 expression in the epidermis

column3: Eruption of permanent teeth behind deciduous (baby) teeth before they have fallen out, resulting in a double row of teeth. This phenomen is typically observed between the ages of 5 to 7 years.
Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the wall of the small intestine.
column8: Hyalinization of the small intestinal walls
